Asked at an event Thursday in New York whether his company would consider offering a direct-to-consumer platform for its content, he gave a nuanced response.Considering about half of the company's revenue comes from affiliate fees, Discovery wouldn't want to jeopardize the "dual-stream" model, Mr. Zaslav said, adding that it works for consumers "at least for now." But, he continued, should a moment arise where such a platform would make sense, Discovery would be ready for it. "We certainly could put together a terrific offering," he said.Like HBO, which launched HBO Go in 2010, Discovery owns almost all of its content. And Discovery already owns online-video site Revision3. One reason it bought the site, was to gain experience in streaming, Mr. Zaslav said. When it comes to online video, Discovery may be sharpening its pocketknife.
